1. Objective¶

World Health Organization(WHO) began their journey on 7 April 1948 a date we now celebrate every year as World Health Day. WHO has are now more than 7000 people from more than 150 countries. They work closely with decision-makers: Ministries of Health, government agencies, other government departments at the national level. Their engagement with the United Nations at the global, regional, and country-level is also a major asset. WHO wants to make people aware of the causes affecting the Child mortality rate. As child deaths occur due to various factors and factors vary from country to country. It becomes very much important to understandthe countries demographics before starting any campaign.

In order to start a campaign around the world, our stakeholders, the board members of WHO need to have all the necessary information that will help decide the kind of campaigns to run. It might help them in distibuting the resources in a more organized and efficient manner, which can save a lot of man power, money and other medical resources as well. So, those saved resources can be used elsewhere thus improving child healthcare globally.

For carrying out this analysis, the dataset is collected from the Global Heath Observatory (GHO), WHO's gateway to health related statistics for more that 1000 indicators for 194 counutries. Which contains the data for different diseases that cause child deaths for each country. The Data are organized to monitor progress towards the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), including health status indicators to monitor progress towards for the overall health goal, indicators to track equity in health indicators, and the indicators for the specific health and health-related targets of the SDGs.

3. Data Cleaning¶

The data cleaning process involves three main steps:

  1. Remove the top 3 rows from all dataframes which include descriptions that are not actual data points
  2. Keep only column "2017.2" in all dataframes which represents the number/rate of child deaths for 0-4 years in 2017
  3. Re-name the columns to identify cause of death in all 12 dataframes
  4. Merge the 12 "2017.2" columns along with one "Country Name" column to create final clean data set
  5. Convert the columns to numeric type

4. Adaptation¶

The following additional columns are created to further our analysis:

  1. Total number of child deaths by country = "total_number"
  2. Total rate of child deaths by country = "total_rate"
  3. % of deaths caused by illness (i.e deaths caused by malaria, hiv/aids & respiratory infection)
  4. % of deaths caused by trauma and prematurity
In [12]:
child_deaths["total_number"] = child_deaths[["malaria", "hivaids", "respiratory", "trauma", "prematurity", 
                                             "other_conditions"]].sum(axis=1)

child_deaths["total_rate"] = child_deaths[["malaria_rate", "hivaids_rate", "respiratory_rate", "trauma_rate", "prematurity_rate", 
                                             "other_conditions_rate"]].sum(axis=1)

child_deaths["illness_causes"] = child_deaths[["malaria", "hivaids", "respiratory"]].sum(axis=1)/child_deaths["total_number"]

child_deaths["non_illness_causes"] = child_deaths[["trauma", "prematurity"]].sum(axis=1)/child_deaths["total_number"]

def piechart():
    labels = ['Malaria', 'HIV/AIDS', 'Respiratory Illness', 'Birth Asphyxia/Trauma', 'Prematurity','Other factors']
    sizes = [Totalmalaria, Totalhivaids, Totalrespiratory, Totaltrauma, Totalprematurity, Totalother_conditions]
#colors
    colors = ['#ff9999','#55bb55','#66b3ff','#99ff99','#ffcc99','#66ccff']
    fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
    patches, texts, autotexts = ax1.pie(sizes, colors = colors, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)
    for text in texts:
        text.set_color('black')
    for autotext in autotexts:
        autotext.set_color('black')
# Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle
    ax1.axis('equal')  
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.title("Pie chart of the Disease causing Child Deaths in the world for year 2017.")
    
    return(plt.show())

piechart()

The pie chart above shows us the percentage of child deaths by different causes at the global level. As we can see, the leading cause is premature births, which accounts for almost 30% of all child deaths. The second leading cause for child deaths is respiratory illness followed by birth asphyxia/trauma.

5.5 Correlation¶

In [40]:
def correlation():
    causes= pd.concat([child_deaths["country"],
                   child_deaths["malaria_rate"].astype(float),
                   child_deaths["hivaids_rate"].astype(float),
                   child_deaths["respiratory_rate"].astype(float),
                   child_deaths["prematurity_rate"].astype(float),      
                   child_deaths["trauma_rate"].astype(float),
                   child_deaths["other_conditions_rate"].astype(float)],axis =1)
    causes.set_index("country", inplace = True)
    corr = causes.corr()
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    cax = ax.matshow(corr,cmap='coolwarm', vmin=0.6,vmax=1)
    fig.colorbar(cax)
    ticks = np.arange(0,len(causes.columns),1)
    ax.set_xticks(ticks)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    ax.set_yticks(ticks)
    ax.set_xticklabels(causes.columns)
    ax.set_yticklabels(causes.columns)
    return(plt.show())

correlation()

The above correlation shows that respiratory, trauma and other_conditions are higly correlated with each other. Which help us to understand that in most countries child deaths by birth_asphyxia/trauma has strong connection with child deaths by respiratory and other_Conditons and vice versa. Where as Prematurity also shows high correlation with Birth_Asphyxia/Trauma.

6. Step by Step Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [21]:
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import euclidean_distances

def agglomerative(df):
    z = 1
    co=-26
    df = causes
    dist_df = pd.DataFrame(euclidean_distances(df))
    dist_df = dist_df.round(3)
    dist_df = dist_df.replace(0, 9999) # Replace 0 with 9999 to find smallest distance b/w different points only
    
    # Iterate through all points 
    while z < len(df.index):
        smallest = dist_df.min().min()
        for i in dist_df.index:
            for j in dist_df.columns:
                if dist_df.loc[i,j] == smallest:
                    merge1 = i 
                    merge2 = j
                if dist_df.loc[i,j] == smallest: break
            if dist_df.loc[i,j] == smallest: break

        
        # Create a new row by picking the smallest distance between new cluster and all other points
        new_row = []
        for i in dist_df.columns:
            min_i = min(dist_df.loc[merge1,i], dist_df.loc[merge2,i])
            new_row.append(min_i)

        new_ix = str(merge1)+"/"+str(merge2)    
        dist_df.loc[new_ix] = new_row
        new_row.append(9999)
        dist_df[new_ix] = new_row
        dist_df = dist_df.drop(index=[merge1, merge2], columns=[merge1, merge2])

        
        #print(dist_df)
        if (z in [1, 25, 100, 150, 193]): 
            print("---After", z," Iterations---")
            print("total number of clusters left:", len(dist_df))
            co=co+5
            print("last ",-co," cluster's ", dist_df.index[co:])
            print("--------------------------------------------")
            if z==193:
                print("All merged into one Big cluster")

        z = z + 1
        
    return(dist_df)

The code above defines a function for agglomerative hierarchical clustering on the child mortality data. The function uses a loop to iterate through the algorithm. In each iteration 1 row and 1 column is reduced in the distance matrix because it joins two clusters.

8. Step by Step K-means¶

In [24]:
def kmeans(df, k):
    centroids = []
    centroids_new = []
    for i in range(k):
        centroids_new.append(np.array([random.uniform(0,1.0), random.uniform(0,1.0), random.uniform(0,1.0), random.uniform(0,1.0), random.uniform(0,1.0)]))
 
    for i in range(50):
        centroids = centroids_new
        np.around(centroids,3)
        centroids = np.reshape(centroids, (4,5))
        df["dist1"] = np.sqrt((df.malaria_rate-centroids[0][0])**2 + (df.hivaids_rate-centroids[0][1])**2 + (df.respiratory_rate-centroids[0][2])**2 + (df.prematurity_rate-centroids[0][3])**2 + (df.trauma_rate-centroids[0][4])**2)
        df["dist2"] = np.sqrt((df.malaria_rate-centroids[1][0])**2 + (df.hivaids_rate-centroids[1][1])**2 + (df.respiratory_rate-centroids[1][2])**2 + (df.prematurity_rate-centroids[1][3])**2 + (df.trauma_rate-centroids[1][4])**2)
        df["dist3"] = np.sqrt((df.malaria_rate-centroids[2][0])**2 + (df.hivaids_rate-centroids[2][1])**2 + (df.respiratory_rate-centroids[2][2])**2 + (df.prematurity_rate-centroids[2][3])**2 + (df.trauma_rate-centroids[2][4])**2)
        df["dist4"] = np.sqrt((df.malaria_rate-centroids[3][0])**2 + (df.hivaids_rate-centroids[3][1])**2 + (df.respiratory_rate-centroids[3][2])**2 + (df.prematurity_rate-centroids[3][3])**2 + (df.trauma_rate-centroids[3][4])**2)
        values = df[["dist1", "dist2", "dist3", "dist4"]]
        #print(values)
        # Identify closest centroid
        df["Association"] = values.idxmin(axis=1) 
        # Recentering centroids
        centroids_new = []
        centroid1_new = df[df.Association == "dist1"][["malaria_rate", "hivaids_rate", "respiratory_rate", "prematurity_rate", "trauma_rate"]].mean()
        centroid2_new = df[df.Association == "dist2"][["malaria_rate", "hivaids_rate", "respiratory_rate", "prematurity_rate", "trauma_rate"]].mean()
        centroid3_new = df[df.Association == "dist3"][["malaria_rate", "hivaids_rate", "respiratory_rate", "prematurity_rate", "trauma_rate"]].mean()
        centroid4_new = df[df.Association == "dist4"][["malaria_rate", "hivaids_rate", "respiratory_rate", "prematurity_rate", "trauma_rate"]].mean()
        centroids_new.append(np.array([centroid1_new, centroid2_new, centroid3_new, centroid4_new]))
        centroids_new = np.reshape(centroids_new, (4,5))
        np.around(centroids_new,3)
        # Check if old and new centroids are the same
        #print(np.array(centroids))
        #print(np.array(centroids_new))
        boolean = np.array(centroids_new)==np.array(centroids)
        #print(boolean)
        #print("end_iter:",i)
        if(boolean.all()==True): break
    return(df, centroids_new)

The code above is used to create a function for implementing the k-means algorithm that accepts a dataframe and k parameter (k = 4 from dendrogram above). We first establish a set of k random centroids the iterate through the k-means algorithm until there is no change in the location of the centroids. The data does not need to be normalized because all columns are on the same scale.

def plotMesh():
    h = 0.1
    # Create color maps
    cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#581845','#900c3f','#c70039','#ffc305'])
    colormap = np.array(['pink', 'red', 'orange','black'])

    x_min2, x_max2 = causes2.other_conditions_rate.min() - 1, causes2.other_conditions_rate.max() + 1
    y_min2, y_max2 = causes2.respiratory_rate.min() - 1, causes2.respiratory_rate.max() + 1
    xx2, yy2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min2, x_max2, h),np.arange(y_min2, y_max2, h))
    Z2 = km.predict(np.c_[xx2.ravel(), yy2.ravel()])

    # Put the result into a color plot
    Z2 = Z2.reshape(xx2.shape)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.pcolormesh(xx2, yy2, Z2, cmap = cmap_light)

    # Plot also the training points
    plt.scatter(causes2.other_conditions_rate, causes2.respiratory_rate, c = colormap[km.labels_], s = 120)
    plt.xlim(xx2.min(), xx2.max())
    plt.ylim(yy2.min(), yy2.max())
    plt.title('violet=cluster0, yellow=cluster3, maron=cluster1, red=cluster2')
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
 #   ax.title("yellow=cluster3, red=cluster2, maron=cluster1, violet=cluster0")
    #title(ax,'Top Plot')
    ax.set_xlabel('other_conditions_rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('respiratory_rate')
plotMesh()

def myKNNfunction(k,vec,dataframe,radius):
# distance from the given point to all other points is calculated and stored in new column called "distance"
    dataframe["distance"] = [0 for x in range(1, len(dataframe.values)+1)]
    for i in range(0, len(dataframe.index)):
        dataframe.distance[i] = np.sqrt((dataframe.trauma_rate[i]-vec[0])**2 + (dataframe.prematurity_rate[i]-vec[1])**2)
    
    totalmembers=0
    currentindex=-1    
# the new sorted dataframe is cretead with distance value in ascending order. 
    new = dataframe.sort_values('distance')

    
# the while loop will look for the points that are within the selected region. 
#By comapring their distances with given "radius".
    while radius > new.distance[currentindex+1]:
        currentindex+=1
        totalmembers+=1
        
        #if there is no other point in the selected region.
    if totalmembers==0:
        return("No cluster found: try increasing radius value.")

    else:
        clust0=0
        clust1=0
        clust2=0
        clust3=0
        
        for j in range(0,totalmembers):
            if new.Association[j]=="cluster0":
                clust0+=1
            if new.Association[j]=="cluster1":
                clust1+=1
            if new.Association[j]=="cluster2":
                clust2+=1
            if new.Association[j]=="cluster3":
                clust3+=1

# Calculate among all the points that which cluster has the majority in the selected region and returns that cluster number.             
        classify =  max(clust0,clust1,clust2,clust3)
        if classify == clust0:
            return("cluster0")
        if classify == clust1:
            return("cluster1")
        if classify == clust2:
            return("cluster2")
        if classify == clust3:
            return("cluster3")

The above myKNNfunction() is the function used to identify the cluster for any new entry. The function takes number of clusters(k), values of the parameter and name of dataframe. It returns the cluster number to which that new entry belongs.

11. Project Report¶

As all the Board members are aware that The World Health Organization (WHO) wants to make people aware of the causes affecting the Child mortality rate and implement global child healthcare campaigns accordingly. As child deaths occur due to various factors and factors vary from country to country. It becomes very important to understand the countries demographics and the differences in causes for death before starting any campaign. The Global Health Observatory data selected for anlaysis includes 6 different causes of child death: malaria, hiv/aids, respiratory illness, birth asphyxia/trauma, prematurity and other conditions. There were 12 tables total: 6 tables showing the number of child deaths by country (one for each cause) & 6 tables showing the rate of child death by country (one for each cause). This report focuses on the most recent data available which is from 2017.

Our analysis is based on answering three important questions:

  1. Which diseases are causing more child deaths all round the world? The pie chart in section 5.1 helps to understand what are the most deadly causes for child deaths around the world. Prematurity & Respiratory Illness are the deadliest accounting for more that 50% of all child deaths.

More than 90% of the countries having higher rate for one of them also has higher rate for the rest.

To understand different ways in which the data can be clustered we created a function that performs agglomerative hierarchical clustering on the dataset. A visual representation of the same analysis can be seen in the Dendrogram in section 7 above. Based on this analysis it was determined that k = 4 (aka 4 clusters) was an appropriate choice when performing clustering analysis on the data.

A kmeans unsupervised learning algorithm is used to cluster the countries in 4 groups. In the first scenerio (section 8) where kmeans is perforemd step by step, all the 6 causes have been selected as parameters for clustering. The mean child mortality rates of every cause is compared between the 4 clusters to find out the most affected cluster. In the second scenerio kmeans is performed using sklear.cluster library in which only two causes that are "respiratory" and "other conditions" are selected to form the clusters.

The next method of clustering was a supervised learning technique: Knn is a algorithm that finds the nearest point among the already plotted points and then decide which cluster to join. Most probably the nearest neighbour are likly to have similar parameters as that of the new point. So a function is created to form cluster of countries for the causes "prematurity" and "brain trauma".

Some important conclusions can be drawn from the clustering analysis:

  • There are significant differences in the average child mortality rates for each cluster
  • Clusters 3 & 4 have very high average child mortality rates compared to Clusters 1 & 2.
  • Clusters 1 & 2 are mainly affected by prematurity and birth asphyxia/trauma
  • Cluster 3, which includes countries like Ethiopia, Kenya, India, Myanmar etc., has a high average for all causes except malaria.
  • Cluster 4 has very high child mortality rates for all 6 causes (including malaria). Countries in this cluster need the most help from WHO. These countries are Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Central African Republic, Chad, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Equatorial Guinea, Guinea, Mali, Niger, Nigeria, Sierra Leone, Somalia, South Sudan, and Togo.

WHO should know that Central Africa Republic, Chad, Somalia, South Sudan, Mali, Serria Leone seems to be having really hard time in addressing thess issues according to all the different clustering methods.

One cause that is prevalent in all the clusters is Birth asphyxia/trauma. This happens when a baby's brain and other organs do not get enough oxygen and nutrients before, during or right after birth. Every other cause of child deaths is linked with Birth asphyxia/trauma. In order to avoid deaths causing due to respiratory illness, prematurity and other conditions special care needs to be taken in three areas.

Camapigns should be targeted towards pregnant women & their families to spread awareness regarding the importance of health care during the different stages of pregnancy. That will help baby to develop to its full potential inside the womb. That might drastically reduce the child deaths rate, especially for birth trauma but also other correlated causes. WHO might want to educate women about all this causes for child deaths and should provide the necessary supplements & medications to the mother that can be used if needed. Additionally, efforts should me made to start Small clinics that provide necessay medication & other treatments to baby after their birth. That will expoentailly reduce the child_death rate for that region.

Only few women/families needs to be made aware about all these causes and their remedies in a particular region. We hope that afterwards those women will enlighten their fellow women as well about the causes and remedies in a particular region. Children are the future of any nation and all countries want to secure their future. WHO alongside the governments & citizens of the respective countries should take initatives to the brighter future.
